ANTHRAX, CATTLE - USA (MONTANTA)
********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html
Date: Wed, 26 May 1999 22:17:06 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: The Billings Gazette (edited)

A group of cows near Billings may have died from anthrax, according a
veterinarian in the state's Department of Livestock. Dr. Tom Linsfield said
further tests would be needed to say for sure if anthrax, a deadly
bacterial disease, killed the cows. The animals died suddenly last week.
"We're investigating a disease outbreak over there," Linsfield said.
He said he expected to know for certain what killed the cows by today, but
said anthrax turned up as the culprit in preliminary tests on the animals.
Until the investigation is over, however, Linsfield said he would not
confirm what killed the cows and would not say exactly where or how many
cows died. "We want to try to get as much info as we can," he said.
Anthrax is a bacteria that lives in alkaline soils, he said. It can become
buried in the soil and remain dormant for years. A heavy rain, which washes
the bacteria to the surface, can cause the bacteria to become infectious
again.
People who come into contact with the hair, feces or hides of an infected
animal can catch anthrax, according to the American Heritage Dictionary. In
humans, anthrax causes ulcers or lesions on the skin.
No people around the suspicious cattle deaths show any signs of the
disease, Linsfield said. So far, no other cows in the area have died.
"There appears to be no further problem," he said.
